history.content:
- do not skip lectures 

- do not skip discussions

- do not skip labs

- read the textbooks

- do not ask for others' help unless you have been stuck on a particular problem for more than 1 hour

- do ALL practice exams before the actual ones

- complete ALL discussion worksheets

- do not find excuses for yourself

---

Follow the course as it's being taught right now, and/or watch past lectures if you're going to have a different professor.

Complete current/past assignments.

You could even go to discussions (if not full) and office hours right now and ask questions as if you are a current student in the course.

Good luck!

---

Get some practice coding in Java as well! It both makes projects easier and builds intuition for the questions that will be asked in CS61B.

children.subject: What do you think I should review, in terms of CS61A content?

imo not a lot of the actual content from 61a transferred over to 61b. what transferred is the general way of thinking about code. i think your time would be much better spent just following the current semester's 61b class and doing research on your own on data structures/algorithms.

Projects in 61b are 50% of your grade (at least with Hilfinger). Maybe review lectures right now, and download the code for a project and try it out. At least for my semester, we were able to test our code locally for the most part.

history.content:
I took CS 61A over the summer and got a C (first midterm covering up to linked lists and trees, scored above the median + mean, completely bombed the second midterm <10% score)

Since I cannot retake 61A, what would be some advice on which materials to review in order to ensure I do well in 61B?

Ideally I want to hit an A and I have my free time this semester to prepare for it.

Thank you in advance.
